oornima during Pushkar Festival. After taking a bath and purifying oneself in the famous Pushkar Lake, devout pilgrims go to the temple. One of the top 10 most spiritual locations in the world, the Brahma Temple is regarded as one of the five holiest pilgrimage sites for Hindus. The Ways to Get here: Buses depart from Ajmer station every hour. Cabs and tuk-tuks are also available. Locations to see which are close to Brahma Temple are Ajmer16 km, Jodhpur 186 km, and Jaipur 145 km. Brahma Temple Rd. in Ganahera, Pushkar, Rajasthan 305022 is the address. Opening times are from 5:00 am to 1:30 pm every day. Free entry. 3. Gurudwara Singh Sabha: Starting in the early 19th century, the eastern part of Pushkar's Gurudwara Singh Sabha was built to honour the visits of the first and tenth gurus, Guru Nanak Dev and Guru Govind Singhji. Location: Pushkar, Rajasthan 305022, across from Indian Overseas Bank. Open all the time. 4. Varaha temple: The Varaha Temple is Pushkar's biggest and oldest temple. This temple was built by King Anaji Chauhan in the 12th century and honoured Lord Vishnu's third appearance as a wild boar. The mythology says that Varaha prevented a devil from dragging the earth into the primordial ocean (Hirnayaksh). One of Pushkar's most visited temples is this one. The Varaha Temple was destroyed by Mughal emperor Aurangzeb because he found the temple's representation of a man's body with a boar's head offensive. In 1727, the temple was restored by Raja Sawai Jai Singh II. Pushkar Main Market, Rajasthan 305022, is the address. Opening times are from 5:00 am to 1:30 pm every day. Free entry. 5. Savitri temple: This temple is situated on a mountain just behind the Brahma temple and is dedicated to Lord Brahma's first wife, Goddess Savitri. One may get a panoramic view of the lake, nearby temples, and dunes while acclimating to the long flight of steps leading to the temple. Savitri cursed Brahma for marrying Gayatri while beginning his yagna at Pushkar; that's why there is only one Brahma Temple in Pushkar. The goddesses Savitri and Gayatri's idols are kept at the temple. You can go through Ratnagiri Hill to reach the temple as the route goes through many hills. This trip is particularly crucial from a religious perspective since it is seen as a form of atonement for our sins. Address: Kharekhari Rd, Pushkar, Rajasthan 305022 The doors are open every day from 5:00 am to 1:30 pm. Entry is free. 6. Rangji Temple: Another well-known temple that attracts many pilgrims and visitors each year is the graceful and striking Rangji Temple. Lord Rangji, who is said to be an avatar of Lord Vishnu, is the subject of the temple. The temple's architecture influences South Indian, Rajput, and Mughal styles. Another aspect of the temple that attracts tourists is the tall "Gopuram," which is mostly found in temples in South India. Location: Rajasthan, Pushkar 305022 Opening times are from 5:00 am to 1:30 pm every day. Free entry. 7. Rose Garden: Pushkar is surprisingly well-known for its rose growing. The Rajasthan Rose Garden is the name given to Rose Garden. The farmers in this area raise a lot of different varieties of roses, which are exported all over the world. Various coloured, fragrant, and stunning red roses cover acres of farmland, enticing one to relax and spend some beautiful time. Travel to these popular Pushkar tourism destinations for an unforgettable trip with your loved ones. Activities: Take a seat, unwind, and rest while taking in the fascinating fragrance of roses. 8. Naga Pahar: The Naga Pahar hills separate Pushkar from Ajmer. According to mythology, the hills of Naga Pahar are still eroding and may soon totally disappear. The famous Sage Agastya is thought to have lived among these mountains. Nag Kund Lake is located in the mountains as well. From its height, Naga Pahar provides a magnificent view of Pushkar and is a popular destination for photographers to take pictures. It is among the top sites in Pushkar to come f